  #affiliated_studies.tab-pane

    %h4
      Genetic and Environmental Risks for Inflammatory Bowel Disease Study
    %p
      %strong Description:
    %p
      This study is looking at genes and environmental factors, such as diet and gut bacteria, that may be associated with developing Crohn’s disease or
      ulcerative colitis.
    %p
      %strong Researcher:
    %p
      Dr. Ramnik Xavier and Dr. Deanna Nguyen at the MGH Crohn’s and Colitis Center
    %p
      %strong Who can participate?
    %p
      This study aims to recruit at least two first-degree family members (you and a parent, sibling, or offspring aged 7 years and older) with inflammatory
      bowel disease and at least one family member without any autoimmune diseases.
    %p
      %strong What would I have to do?
    %p
      Participants in this study will be asked to:
    %ul{:type => "disc"}
      %li
        provide a saliva or blood sample
      %li
        provide an optional urine and stool sample
      %li
        complete study related activities by phone, email, or postal service


    %hr/
    %br/
    %h4
      Defining the Genetic Architecture of Crohn’s Disease in the Ashkenazi Jewish Population
    %p
      %strong Description:
    %p
      This study will look how Ashkenazim specific genetic variants contribute to Crohn’s disease.
    %p
      %strong Researcher:
    %p
      Dr. Judy Cho at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai, New York.
    %p
      %strong Who can participate?
    %p
      Adult members of CCFA Partners who report Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry
    %p
      %strong What would I have to do?
    %p
      Participants in this study will be asked to:
    %ul
      %li
        Provide a saliva sample
      %li
        Provide IBD-related medical and family history
    %p
      · Complete study-related activities by phone, email, or postal service.


    %hr/
    %br/
    %h4
      Patient-Valued Preferences for Risk and Effectiveness of Medical and Surgical Therapies in Ulcerative Colitis
    %p
      %strong Description:
    %p
      This study will look how a new patient-driven online educational tool influences patient perspectives on medical and surgical treatment options for
      patients with Ulcerative Colitis.
    %p
      %strong Researcher:
    %p
      Dr. Meenakshi Bewtra at the University of Pennsylvania
    %p
      %strong Who can participate?
    %p
      Adult members of CCFA Partners with Ulcerative Colitis.
    %p
      %strong What would I have to do?
    %p
      Participants in this study will be asked to complete an online questionnaire


    %hr/
    %br/
    %h4
      Multi-Center African American IBD Study (MAAIS)
    %p
      %strong Description:
    %p
      This study is looking at genes and environmental factors that may be associated with developing inflammatory bowel disease.
    %p
      %strong Researcher:
    %p
      Dr. Steven Brant from Johns Hopkins School of Medicine
    %p
      %strong Who can participate?
    %p
      Adult members of CCFA Partners who self-identify as being African American
    %p
      %strong What would I have to do?
    %p
      Participants in this study will be asked to sign a consent form, fill out a written questionnaire and contribute about 3 tablespoons of blood. Your spouse
      or friend that does not have IBD may also be eligible to join this study as a healthy volunteer. Compensation includes $40.00 for all participants for
      enrollment. An additional $10.00 referral fee may also be available.


    %hr/
    %br/
    %h4
      OTIS Autoimmune Diseases In Pregnancy Study
    %p
      %strong Description:
    %p
      The purpose of the study is to collect data on children born to mothers with inflammatory bowel disease. Researchers will evaluate the risk of birth
      defects in children of patients exposed to certain medications during pregnancy.
    %p
      %strong Researcher:
    %p
      Dr. Christina Chambers of University of California San Diego (UCSD)
    %p
      %strong Who can participate?
    %p
      Women diagnosed with Crohn’s disease or ulcerative colitis who are pregnant. Must have been pregnant for less than 20 weeks.
    %p
      %strong What would I have to do?
    %p
      If you choose to participate, you will undergo telephone interviews and provide medical records to researchers from the OTIS Registry. Children born to
      mothers who participate would be followed for up to 5 years for growth and development (with review of their medical records), including in-person
      examinations and testing in the first year and in the time period between 3.5 and 5 years.
      %strong

    %hr/
    %br/
    %p
      CCFA Partners will notify you via email if you qualify for any of the studies described here.